<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
Frequently reported from Greece, considered cosmopolitan (
<bibRefCitation author="Pleijel, Fredrik" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="2547 - 2566" title="A revision of Hesiospina (Psamathini, Hesionidae, Polychaeta)" volume="38" year="2004">Pleijel 2004</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Simboura, Nomiki" journalOrPublisher="PhD thesis. National and Kapodistrian University of Athens, Athens" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" title="Θαλάσσοι μακροβενθικοί Πολύxαιτοι (AnnelidaPolychaeta) της Ελλάδας: Συστηματική, Οικολογία, Ζωογεωγραφία" year="1996">Simboura (1996)</bibRefCitation>
notes morphological differences between specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Hesionidae" genus="Hesiospina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesiospina similis" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="similis">Hesiospina similis</taxonomicName>
from the Mediterranean and from the native range (Japan). Specifically, Mediterranean material exhibits a stronger serration of the blades of the compound chaetae and neuropodial aciculae with rounded instead of tapering tips.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
